<p><ent>Stang</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stang
<hw>Stang</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>stange</ets>, of Scand. or
Dutch origin; cf. Icel. <ets>st⟦oum⟧ng</ets>, akin to Dan.
<ets>stang</ets>, Sw. <ets>st⟦aring⟧ng</ets>, D. <ets>stang</ets>, G.
<ets>stange</ets>, OHG. <ets>stanga</ets>, AS. <ets>steng</ets>; from
the root of E. <ets>sting</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A long bar; a
pole; a shaft; a stake.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In land measure, a pole, rod, or perch.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stang ball</b></col>, <cd>a projectile consisting of two
half balls united by a bar; a bar shot. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<cref>Bar shot</cref>, under <er>Bar</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To ride the
stang</b></col>, <cd>to be carried on a pole on men's shoulders. This
method of punishing wife beaters, etc., was once in vogue in some parts
of England.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stang</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stang
<hw>Stang</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Akin to <ets>sting</ets>; cf.
Icel. <ets>stanga</ets> to prick, to goad.]</ety> <def>To shoot with
pain.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanhope</ent>⟦br⟧
